column168: Description Of Events

THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF THE DRUM NOZZLE BEING CLOSED WHILE PUMP WAS ENGAGED.  EXCESS PRESSURE CAUSED THE HOSE END TO COME OFF WHILE THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH RAGS BY THE DRIVER AND TERMINAL SUPERVISOR.  CONSIGNEE DISPOSED OF THE RAGS.

DRIVER HAD A PROBLEM WITH THE HOSE CONNECTION AND SUBSEQUENTLY LEAKED. THERE WAS ALSO A LEAK AT THE PUMP PACKING.  FIVE GALLON BUCKETS WERE USED TO CAPTURE LEAKS.  CONSIGNEE HANDLED CAPTURED PRODUCT IN THE FIVE GALLON BUCKETS AND CLEANED UP ANY SPILLAGE.

CONTENTS OF PACKAGE NOTED TO CONTAIN POISON HAD BEEN LOADED WITH FOOD STUFF AND WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER WHEN THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT PIERCED THE CARTON ON THEN DOCK.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE OCCURRED BEFORE THE CARTON COULD BE LEANED OVER TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.  ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A HAZ MAT CONTAINMENT DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

THE FREIGHT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE THE TRAILERS WAS BEING UNLOADED. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND RECOUP INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED ABOUT THE FORKLIFT DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT THAT THEY LOADED ON CON-WAYS TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT FREIGHT CLOSER THAT HAS BE LOADED BY THE SHIPPER, TO MAKE SURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

DRIVER OVERFILLED TANK.  APPROX. 50 GALLONS OF RED DIESEL SPILLED. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, HE WAS ADVISED BY PERSONNEL NOT TO WORRY ABOUT SPILLAGE DUE TO RETENTION WALL.  HOWEVER AFTER A CLOSER INSPECTION BY PERSONNEL IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE ON THE REAR OF THE RETENTION WALL WAS OPEN AND A PORTION OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT DRAINED OUT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY PERSONNEL OF TMPA.
APPROX. 30-50 GALLONS OF DIESEL SPILLED.  TANK OVERFILLED.  COMMUNICATION ERROR BETWEEN DISPATCH AND CUSTOMER.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY OWNER.

column168: APEX ENVIROTECH, INC. (APEX) IS PLEASED TO PROVIDE CARTER ENERGY, INC. (CARTER) WITH THIS RESULTS REPORT FOR A LIMITED SUBSURFACE INVESTIGATION AT AND AROUND NABLUS CONOCO (SITE) LOCATED AT 6865 STATE AVENUE, KANSAS CITY, KANSAS (FIGURE 1).  THIS REPORT DOCUMENTS THE SITE INVESTIGATION OF A RELEASE OF 129.5 GALLONS OF UNLEADED REGULAR GASOLINE THAT OCCURRED DURING A PRODUCT DELIVERY TO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS (USTS) ON 02/12/04.  SITE AND INCIDENT DESCRIPTION.  THE SITE IS A RETAIL MOTOR FUELS STATION WITH ATTACHED CONVENIENCE STORE AND OFFICE (FIGURE 2).  THERE ARE TWO, 7300 GALLON USTS ON THE PREMISES.  THE SITE IS BOUNDED ON THE NORTH AND WEST BY STATE AVENUE AND N. 69TH ST., RESPECTIVELY.  A BODY SHOP ENTERPRISE IS ADJACENT AND CONTIGUOUS ON THE EAST AND SOUTH SIDES OF THE SITE (FIGURE 2). REMODELING OF THE INSIDE AND OUTSIDE OF THE OFFICE AND CONVENIENCE STORE WAS IN PROGRESS AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE, HOWEVER NO CONSTRUCTION WORKERS WERE ON SITE AT THE TIME.  ON THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 12 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 AM, A RELEASE OF REGULAR UNLOADED GASOLINE TOOK PLACE AT THE SITE.  VERBAL REPORTS FROM THE SITE PERSONNEL AND OTHERS INDICATE THE GASOLINE ESCAPED DURING FUELING AND BEGAN FLOWING DOWNSLOPE TO THE WEST TOWARD N. 69TH STREET.  A CUTOUT IN THE CURB ON THE WEST EASEMENT OF THE SITE THEN ALLOWED THE GAS TO FLOW DIRECTLY SOUTH ON N. 69TH STREET FOR APPROXIMATELY 220 FEET TRAVERSING THE EASEMENT IN FRONT OF THE RESIDENCE AT 1011 N 69TH STREET, AND ULTIMATELY CROSSING N 69TH STREET AND TERMINATING AT THE EDGE OF THE WEST SIDE OF THE PAVEMENT (FIGURE 3).  THE GASOLINE APPEARS TO HAVE STAYED IN THE RIGHT-OF-WAY OF N. 69TH ST. AND UTILITY EASEMENT DRAINAGE AREA AND DID NOT COME IN CONTACT WITH ANY RESIDENTIAL PROPERTY ALONG N. 69TH STREET. CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF THE RELEASE INCLUDED BELOW FREEZING TEMPERATURES, ABUNDANT ICE AND SNOW IN THE SITE PARKING LOT, ON THE STREETS AND IN THE STREET DRAINAGE ALONG THE PATH OF THE GASOLINE TRAVEL.  THE GROUND ITSELF WAS FROZEN SEVERAL INCHES INTO THE SUBSURFACE.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING EAST ON POUNCY TRACT RD ON A RELATIVELY STRAIGHT SECTION OF THE ROAD WHEN HE ENCOUNTERED ANOTHER TRUCK COMING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION.  THE OTHER TRUCK WAS CROWDING THE CENTERLINE.  IN AN EFFORT TO AVOID THE OTHER TRUCK OUR DRIVER PULLED TO THE RIGHT JUST AS THE ROAD BEGAN TO BEND SLIGHTLY BACK TO THE LEFT.  THE RIGHT WHEELS LEFT THE ROAD AND TRACKED INTO A SOFT GRASSY SHOULDER.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GET THE TRUCK BACK ON THE ROAD AND WHEN THE RIGHT FRONT WHEELS HIT THE PAVEMENT THE TRUCK BEGAN TO ROLL TOWARD THE PASSENGER SIDE.  IT ROLLED OVER TWO OR THREE TIMES COMING TO REST IN A FIELD NEXT TO THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE TRUCK THROUGH THE PASSENGER SIDE AND SUFFERED A LACERATION TO HIS LEFT HAND BETWEEN THE THUMB AND INDEX FINGER.  OTHERWISE HE EXPERIENCED CONSIDERABLE BRUISING AND SORENESS BUT NO SERIOUS INJURIES AS FAR AS WE CAN TELL.  HE WAS TREATED AT MCV HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  THE DRIVER WAS WEARING HIS SEAT BELT.  APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF OIL WAS LOST ONTO THE GROUND THROUGH PUNCTURES IN THE TANK.  THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING APPROXIMATELY 1600 GALLONS AT THE TIME AND 900 GALLONS OF IT WAS PUMPED INTO THE VAC TRUCK PROVIDED BY JL BISHOP AND DISPOSED OF.  ANOTHER 200+ GALLONS WAS TRANSFERRED TO A MARSH OIL FUEL TRUCK.  JL BISHOP RETURNED THE FOLLOWING DAY TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  THE COST OF CLEANUP IS ESTIMATED AT $7,500.00.  THERE WAS DAMAGE TO THE VERIZON TELEPHONE JUNCTION TOWER LOCATED IN THE GRASSY AREA WHERE THE TRUCK ROLLED.  ESTIMATED DAMAGE $1500.00.

AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45 A.M. ON 2/23/04 APPROXIMATELY 50 LBS. OF K061 BAGHOUSE DUST WAS RELEASED FROM A PAGE E.T.C. TRANSPORT TRAILER.  THE PAGE DRIVER HAD LOADED HIS TRUCK WITH BAGHOUSE DUST AND NOTICED THAT THE TRUCK WAS OVERLOADED O THE FRONT AXLES.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO EQUALIZE THE LOAD USING HIS BRAKES.  THIS DID NOT WORK SO HE THEN BEGAN RAISING THE TRUCK BED TO SHIFT THE LOAD TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  RAISING THE BED OF THE TRUCK RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 50 LBS. OF MATERIAL SPILLING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK BETWEEN THE TAILGATE AND TARP.  THE SPILL OCCURRED ON MACSTEEL MONROE, INC. PROPERTY, MORE SPECIFICALLY, AT THE EAST END OF THE SOUTH SCRAP ROAD.  WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED A HYDRO TECHNOLOGY, INC. EMPLOYEE WHO WAS WORKING IN THE AREA. THE TRUCK WAS NOT MOVED.  HYDRO TECHNOLOGY, INC. IS MACSTEEL MONROE'S ONSITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED USING CAUTION TAPE.  HYDRO TECHNOLOGY BEGAN CLEANING UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE ROAD AND THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AT APPROXIMATELY 10:45 A.M.  THE MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM THE ROAD USING A VACUUM TRUCK, OIL ABSORBENT, A BROOM AND WIRE BRUSH.  THE MATERIAL WAS PILED ONTO AN UNPAVED SLAG ROAD THAT HAS BEEN TREATED REPEATEDLY WITH AN ASPHALT RESIN DUST SUPPRESSANT.  THE SURFACE OF THE ROAD WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED IS VERY HARD DUE TO YEARS OF DUST SUPPRESSANT BEING APPLIED. HYDRO TECHNOLOGY COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP AT APPROXIMATELY 3:50 P.M.  THE NRC WAS CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15 A.M., THE MDEQ-PEAS WAS CONTACTED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:21 A.M., AND THE LEPC WAS CONTACTED AT 10:31 A.M.  AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 A.M. MACSTEEL MONROE, INC. RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. BILL YOCUM OF THE MDEQ-WHMD.  I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO MR. YOCUM, SPECIFICALLY, THE CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES THAT WERE IN PROGRESS.  ALSO, I EXPLAINED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ONTO A HARD SURFACE AND THAT THE BAGHOUSE DUST HAS A DISTINCTIVE RED/RUST COLOR WHICH MADE IT EASY TO DISTINGUISH FROM THE BACKGROUND COLOR OF THE ROAD.  MR. YOCUM THEN REQUESTED THAT SWAB SAMPLES BE TAKEN FROM THE AREA TO VERIFY THAT THE MATERIAL WAS ADEQUATELY REMEDIATED.  THREE BACKGROUND SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FROM OTHER AREAS OF THE SAME ROADWAY THAT WAS NOT AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE, AND ONE SAMPLE WAS TAKEN FROM THE CLEANED AREA.  SWAB SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 P.M.  THESE SAMPLES WERE SUBMITTED TO MIDWEST ANALYTICAL SERVICES, INC. AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 A.M. ON 2/24/04. MACSTEEL MONROE, INC. RECEIVED THE SAMPLE RESULTS ON 2/25/04.  THE ANALYTICAL RESULTS ARE ATTACHED.  MR YOCUM ALSO REQUESTED THAT PHOTOGRAPHS BE TAKEN BEFORE AND AFTER THE CLEAN UP WHICH ARE ALSO ATTACHED.  THE ROAD WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED SINCE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AND WILL REMAIN CLOSED UNTIL THE FACILITY RECEIVES A RESPONSE THE MDEQ STATING THAT THE CLEAN UP IS COMPLETE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 PM (2030 HOURS) 2/4/04, POLYOL PLANT OPERATIONS PERSONNEL CONNECTED STEAM TO A MDI RAILCAR, GATX 18748.  THIS WAS DONE TO HEAT THE CONTENTS SO THE MATERIAL COULD BE TRANSFERRED TO STORAGE AS PART OF THE SOP.  NO OTHER CONNECTIONS WERE MADE TO THE CAR.  THE CAR TEMPERATURE WAS CHECKED APPROXIMATELY EVERY HOUR.  AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 AM THE CHEMICAL HANDLER OBSERVED THE CAR TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT ALONG THE BOTTOM LENGTH OF THE CAR.  THE MOST PROMINENT AMOUNT APPEARED TO BE NEAR THE "B" END OF THE CAR AND EXTENDING TO THE CENTER OF THE CAR.  THE TOTAL AREA COVER IS ESTIMATED TO BE 150 FT BY 6 FT BY 0.5 FT DEEP RESULTING IS AND ESTIMATED LOSS OF ^ 3375 GALLONS OR ^35000 LBS.  LOSSES WERE CONFIRMED BY A MASS BALANCE.  IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTION OR RESPONSE.  THE CHEMICAL HANDLER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR.  ALL VALVES/DRAINS DISCHARGING WATER FROM THE AREA WERE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED.  THE SUMP FEED TO THE CARBON TREATMENT BEDS WAS SHUT DOWN.  THE SPILL AREA WAS DIKED WITH ABSORBENT PILLOWS AND ZORBALL.  THE PRESSURE PAD ON THE RAILCAR WAS VENTED TO MINIMIZE THE RATE OF THE LEAK.  ONCE THE PAD WAS REMOVED THE VENT VALVE WAS CLOSED TO ALLOW A SMALL VACUUM TO FORM INSIDE THE CAR WHICH RESULTED IN FURTHER SLOWING THE LEAK.  THE PLANT MANAGER, AND SESD ON CALL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED.  THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED BY THE SESD ON CALL PERSON.  SITE SECURITY PERSONNEL WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE ENTIRE AREA WAS EXAMINED TO VERIFY THE SPILL HAD BEEN CONTAINED.  TO MINIMIZE THE SIZE OF THE POOL OF SPILLED MATERIAL A ^50 GALLON TUB WAS PLACED UNDER THE MAJOR LEAK POINT AND WHEN THE TUB FILLED ITS CONTENTS WERE PUMPED TO TOTES. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH LOCAL APPROVED COMPANIES TO PROVIDE RESOURCES TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING CONTENTS TO ANOTHER RAILCAR.  THE EH&S GROUP CONDUCTED AREA AIR MONITORING AT THE MDI LOAD RACK IN SUPPORT OF THE RAIL CAR RESPONSE ON 02/09/04.  DIRECT-READ AREA MONITORING WAS PERFORMED USING A ZELLWEGER (MDA SCIENTIFIC) TLD METER WITH ISOCYANATE CHEMCASSETTE AND MDI KEY.  OVERALL, NO DETECTABLE AIRBORNE CONCENTRATION (DETECTION LIMIT = 2 PPB) WAS NOTED AT ANY LOCATION TESTED. ASHLAND DISTRIBUTION DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 13 DRUMS AT MORGAN ADVANCED CERAMICS WHEN A FORKLIFT DRIVER PUNCTURED A DRUM OF MEK. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED ON IT'S SIDE AND THE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBANT PADS.

WHILE TRANSPORTATION DRUMS OF WASTE TO A FACILITY IN ELIZABETH, NJ, THE TRAILER DISENGAGED FROM THE TRACTOR. THE TRAILER THEN DROPPED TO THE ROAD SURFACE AND IMPACTED THE GUARDRAIL. THE GUARDRAIL PUNCTURED THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND THROUGH TWO DRUM OF WASTE MATERIALS. ABOUT 12-15 FEET OF THE GUARDRAIL ENTERED THE TRAILER. A VERY SMALL LEAK OF AN OILY SUBSTANCE LEAKED FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER, INTO THE SURROUNDING ICE AND SOIL. THE EMERGENCY SERVICES RESPONDED AND ASSISTED IN THE CONTROL OF THE EMERGENCY AND THE LEAK. OUR SISTER COMPANY, CYCLE CHEM, INC., RESPONDED AND PERFORMED THE MITIGATION AND CLEAN UP OPERATIONS. THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR SPECULATED THAT THE FIFTH-WHEEL UNIT ON THE TRACTOR HAD FAILED. THE TRACTOR WAS SENT TO OUR MAINTENANCE SHOP FOR DETAILED INSPECTION.

column168: AT ABOUT 1:30 AM EST, THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT AT CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY.  HE WAS UNAWARE FOR A FEW MINUTES THAT THE CONSIGNEE'S OVERHEAD PIPING BROKE, UNTIL THE LIQUID FALLING ON HIM BEGAN TO BURN HIS EYES AROUND HIS FACE SHIELD AND SAFETY GLASSES.  THE LIQUID HAD SPRAYED OVER THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER AND ON THE PLANT SURFACE.  PLANT PERSONNEL HELD IV DRIVER IN SAFETY SHOWER AND GAVE HIM A BOTTLE OF EYEWASH SOLUTION AFTER WHICH, HIS RIGHT EYE WAS STILL BURNING.  THE CONSIGNEE TOOK HIM TO THE E.R. AT WILLIS KNIGHT MEDICAL CENTER, SHREVEPORT, LA.  AT 4;50 AM- IV DRIVER CALLED BACK FROM THE DIARY (CONSIGNEE) PROPERTY- HAD RETURNED FROM HOSPITAL- TREATED AND RELEASED. CONSIGNEE CAPTURED ALL SPILL MATERIAL IN CONTAINMENT,  AND ESTIMATE NO MORE THAN 10 GALLONS. THEY INDICATED THEY DO NOT NEED CLEANUP  ASSISTANCE FROM US.  THEY CLARIFIED THAT A FITTING HAD COME APART ON THE OVERHEAD LINE.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED PRODUCT SLOSH FROM MANWAY AREA OF UTLX 201293 & THIS RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED IN RAILYARD.  BNSF RESPONDER FOUND 6 OF 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS FINGER LOOSE & THESE WERE PROPERLY TOOL TIGHTENED.  AFTER SECUREMENT COMPLETED, UTLX 201293 WAS MOVED IN RAILYARD TO ENSURE NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE EVIDENT.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT ON TANK SHELL EVAPORATED.

MTL DRIVER WAS LOADED & PULLED ONTO THE SCALES AT THE PLANT.  THE DRIVER & THE OPERATOR CLOSED THE DOME LID & SECURED IT, HOWEVER THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THAT THE CABLE WHICH HELDS THE CHICAGO FITTING CAP HAD GOTTEN CAUGHT UNDER THE LID SEAL AND THIS PREVENTED THE DOME LID FROM SEALING ON THE BACK SIDE AND WHEN THE DRIVER PULLED ONTO THE SCALES TO WEIGH OUT, PRODUCT SPILLED FROM THE LID.  SPILL WAS LESS THAN 3 GAL.  THE PLANT CLEANED THE SPILL BY PICKING SPILL UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SENT TO PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL FOR DISPOSAL.  DRIVER WAS RETRAINED IN CP311 PAJA 435 PROCEDURES BEFORE LOADING A LOADING AREA.
NO REMARKS.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE UNCOUPLED AND SERVICED EARLIER THAT DAY OF THE INCIDENT.  AFTER LOADING THE TRUCK, THE DRIVER PULLED OUT ONTO THE COUNTY ROAD WERE THE TRAILER CAME UN-COUPLED AND THE FRONT/BOTTOM/LEFT SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK CONTACTED THE FRAME OF THE POWER UNIT PUNCTURING A HOLE IN THE CARGO TANK.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK EMPTIED INTO THE WEST ROAD DITCH AND FLOWED 240 FEET TO THE NORTH.  THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS DUG UP AND SPREAD OUT ON THE LAND ADJACENT TO THE DITCH FOR INSITU REMEDIATION APPROVED BY THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT/RELOAD WHEN THE INNER PACKAGE FAILURE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 12 AEROSOL CANS AT APPROXIMATELY 16 OUNCES CAPACITY EACH.  THE VALVE STEM ON ONE OF THE AEROSOLS APPARENTLY FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE FAILED ITEM WAS REMOVED THE PACKAGE AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE OTHER ITEMS WERE RESEALED AND FORWARDED ON TO RECIPIENT PENDING THE DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

column42: HYDRAZINE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, WITH NOT MORE THAN 37 PERCENT HYDRAZINE, BY MASS
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING THIRTY-FIVE HUNDRED POUND STEEL TOTE BIN WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DEFECTIVE GASKET ON THE TOP OF THE TOTE BIN.  A BAYER CHEMICALS HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED FROM ONE OF THEIR WEST VIRGINIA FACILITIES TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE BAYER CHEMICALS HAZMAT TEAM REMOVED ALL WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP, ALONG WITH THE TOTE BIN.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE WET CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING ONE LEAKING SIXTEEN OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS DISCOVERED.  APPROXIMATELY THREE OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE DOCK.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE BOX BEING KNOCKED OVER IN HANDLING, CAUSING THE CAP ON THE BOTTLE TO SNAP AND BREAK.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, GOGGLES, GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, A WHISKBROOM AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE WET BOX AND LEAKING BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO A SEPARATE FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, A TORN FIFTY POUND BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO FRICTION BETWEEN THE BAGS IN THE SHIPMENT.  ADVANCED CLEANUP TECHNOLOGIES OF BAKERSFIELD, CA PERFORMED THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TORN BAG WAS RECOUPED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED THIRTY POUND PLASTIC-LINED PAPER BAG WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTY POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO INSUFFICIENT DUNNAGE ALLOWING A PALLET DECKED ON TOP TO RIP THE BAG.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED BAG, AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A PLASTIC HAZMAT BAG, WHICH WAS THEN PLACED INTO ONE, FORTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS AN ODOR WAS DETECTED IN THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED UNTIL INVESTIGATION BY THE HAZMAT TEAM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED AN INVESTIGATION USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED NEAR THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED NINE METAL DRUMS CONTAINING THE SAME MATERIAL.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FAULTY SEAM ON THE DRUM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, DUNNAGE, ABSORBENTS, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE NINE AFFECTED DRUMS WERE CLEANED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: VEHICLE WAS EASTBOUND ON EDWARDS ROAD.  DRIVER WAS GOING TO FAST FOR CURVE ONTO NORTH ANTELOPE ROAD CAUSING TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OVERTURN.  THE CARGO TANK DID NOT RUPTURE.  THE HAZMAT TEAM INSISTED ON DRILLING A 4 INCH HOLE IN THE UPSIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THEY DID NOT DRILL IT FAR ENOUGH UP AND ALSO FAILED TO PUMP OFF ALL OF THE PRODUCT.  THEY ALSO FAILED TO PLACE A PLUG IN THE HOLE.  WHEN THE TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED PRODUCT STARTED FLOWING FROM THE HOLE.  WHEN THE TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED PRODUCT STARTED FLOWING FROM THE HOLE.  MY CREW RAN AND STUFFED RAGS IN THE HOLE STOPPING THE PRODUCT. TOTAL AMOUNT SPILLED WAS 1 1/2 BARRELS.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS TAKEN TO THE CUSTOMER AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  NO DAMAGE TO SOIL.  THIS SPILLAGE COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF THE HAZMAT TEAM HAD LISTEN TO INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE CARRIER REPRESENTATIVE AT THE SCENE.  THAT BEING, PLACING A PLUG INTO THE HOLE DRILLED AND DRILLING THE HOLE FURTHER UP ON THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER.

column168: OUR DELIVERY DRIVER HAD SHUT DOWN HIS UNIT AFTER MAKING A DELIVERY TO A RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMER.  DRIVER WAS TRYING TO UNTANGLE HIS HOSE WHEN HE DROPPED THE NOZZLE.  WHEN IT HIT THE GROUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID PROPANE SHOT OUT OF THE NOZZLE AND HIT DRIVER JUST ABOVE HIS LEFT KNEE AND ON HIS GROIN AREA.  DRIVER DROVE HIMSELF TO THE CLINIC THERE WAS REDNESS AND WATER BLISTERS - 1ST & SECOND DEGREE BURNS.  DRIVER WAS GIVEN WORK RESTRICTIONS BUT WAS NEVER WRITTEN OFF WORK.  DRIVER WAS WEARING HIS PROTECTIVE UNIFORM PANTS.  NO EVAC, NO ROAD CLOSURE, DRIVER HAS ANOTHER DR'S APPT NEXT WEEK.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: HIGHWAY TRANSPORT DRIVER MOVED A TRUCK, WITHOUT PERMISSION, WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF BEING LOADED.  THE TRAILER WAS CHOCKED AND PROPERLY GROUNDED, IN ADDITION, THE STEPS WERE DOWN ON THE TRAILER AND THE HOIST WAS IN THE DOWN POSITION.  DAMAGE OCCURRED TO THE TRUCK'S DOME LID AND THE LOADING RACK AS HE PULLED THE TRUCK FORWARD.  THE LOADING HOSE RUPTURED, SPILLING FORMALDEHYDE INTO A RETENTION SUMP AT THE LOAD AREA.  HOW THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED: WHEN THE DRIVER HEARD THE CRASH. CONTRIBUTING FACTORS TO THIS INCIDENT: DRIVER TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY, STATING HE DECIDED TO HELP OUT BY MOVING THE TRUCK.  INTERIM ACTIONS TAKEN:  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE AND ENGAGED THE PUMP EMERGENCY STOP BUTTON.  GPRI PERSONNEL SECURED ALL VALVES AND CONTAINED THE SPILL TO THE RETENTION SUMP. SUGGESTIONS TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT FROM REOCCURRING: A CHANGE IN PROCEDURES WILL REQUIRE COLLECTING OF TRUCK KEYS BY GPRI PERSONNEL PRIOR TO LOADING OF TANKERS.

column168: AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S SOUTH PHILADELPHIA YARD IN PHILADELPHIA, PA, THE CONDUCTOR ON YARD JOB Y302 REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, RPBX17106, LOAD PHOSPHORIC ACID, HAD SLOSHED PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHEN IT WAS BEING SWITCHED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER, PCS SALES, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PUT ON CROOKED AND WAS DAMAGED WHEN THE COVER WAS BOLTED DOWN.  IT WAS ALSO INDICATED THAT THE MANWAY COVER MIGHT POSSIBLY BE WARPED.  THE CONTRACTOR INSTALLED A REPLACEMENT GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  THE PENNSYLVANIA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: THE CAR INSPECTOR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN PARKERSBURG, WV, REPORTED THAT GATX 90369, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE, WAS EMITTING FUMES AND AN ODOR FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER, E I DUPONT, RESPONDED A TEAM FROM THEIR WASHINGTON WORKS FACILITY.  DUPONT REPORTED THAT THEY PUT ABOUT 15 POUNDS OF NITROGEN ON THESE CARS TO ASSIST IN THE UNLOADING AND TO PROTECT THE PRODUCT'S COLOR.  NITROGEN IS LEFT ON THE CARS AFTER UNLOADING.  WHEN THEY INSPECTED THE CAR, DUPONT FOUND THAT NITROGEN AND A PRODUCT ODOR WERE BEING RELEASED FROM AROUND THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  ACCORDING TO DUPONT, THEY COULD NOT DETERMINE THE EXACT SOURCE OF THE NITROGEN RELEASE, SO THEY BLED NITROGEN PRESSURE OFF THE CAR.  WHEN THE PRESSURE WAS REDUCED, THE NITROGEN LEAK AND ODOR STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  DUPONT INDICATED THAT THE CAR WILL BE INSPECTED WHEN IT RETURNS TO THEIR ORANGE, TX FACILITY.  THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE WV DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.

CSXT DELIVERED THE CAR TO GEO SPECIALTY CHEMICAL ON 02-11-2004.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER CONTACTED GEO SPECIALTY CHEMICAL IN CEDARTOWN, GA. AND WAS ADVISED THAT GEO SPECIALTY HAD PUT ABOUT 5 PSIG ON TCDX11019 IN PREPARATION TO UNLOAD IT, AND VAPORS BEGAN TO LEAK OUT FROM THE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  THE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS BUT THE LEAK PERSISTED.  GEO SPECIALTY THEN CONTACTED CYTECH FOR ASSISTANCE IN GETTING THE MANWAY COVER GASKET REPLACED.

VEHICLE WAS PROCEEDING ON I-5 SOUTHBOUND WHEN DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL LEAK AT THE RUPTURE DISC OVERFLOW TUBE.  DRIVER EXITED THE NEXT OFF-RAMP, WHICH WAS BASILONE ROAD AND PARKED VEHICLE.  DRIVER THEN INSPECTED CARGO TANK TO DETERMINE SOURCE OF LEAK.  DRIVER DETERMINED LEAK WAS FROM A FAILED RUPTURE DISC AND SECURED AREA.  DRIVER MADE PHONE NOTIFICATIONS.  CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL AND SAN DIEGO COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH RESPONDED.  DTI MANAGEMENT ENGAGED OUR ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO PROVIDE CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF SPILLED ACID.  RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED BY DTI MECHANIC AND VEHICLE PROCEEDED TO CONSIGNEE FOR DELIVERY.  CAUSE OF FAILURE IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME, INVESTIGATION IS CONTINUING.  PROCEDURE IN PLACE TO CLOSELY EXAMINE THE RUPTURE DISC ON ALL MC 312 TRAILERS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE AIRGAS WEST DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON THE 210 FREEWAY IN THE CITY OF MONROVIA IN THE SLOW LANE.  HIS SPEED WAS ABOUT 50 MPH.  THE ROADS WERE WET AS IT HAD RAINED ON AND OFF THROUGHOUT THE DAY.  THE AIRGAS WEST DRIVER NOTED THAT A WHITE CAR HAD ENTERED HIS LANE.  IN FRONT OF THE WHITE CAR WAS A MAROON SUV.  THE AIRGAS WEST DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE SUV BRAKE LIGHTS AND THEN SUDDENLY THE WHITE CAR BRAKE LIGHT.  THE AIRGAS WEST DRIVER BRAKED HARD.  THE REAR OF THE TRUCK BEGAN TO MOVE INTO THE LEFT LANE.  HE TOOK HIS FOOT OFF OF THE BRAKE AND ATTEMPTED TO STRAIGHTEN OUT THE TRUCK. UNFORTUNATELY, HE STRUCK THE GUARD RAIL AND BROKE THROUGH.  THE TRUCK OVERTURNED TWICE AND LANDED ON ITS WHEELS.  THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED VIA AMBULANCE TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS DISCHARGED THE NEXT DAY.  AIRGAS WEST HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDERS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND WITH THE PERMISSION OF THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES VENTED OFF THE RESIDUAL ARGON FROM THE BULK CONTAINER (IT WAS NEARLY EMPTY AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT).  THE APPROXIMATE LOSS OF ARGON WAS 50 GALLONS WHICH QUICKLY DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS.

OUR DRIVER WAS MOVING THE TOTE TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO BE OFF LOADED BY THE CUSTOMER'S FORKLIFT OPERATOR.  USING A MANUAL JACK THE DRIVER USED FORCE TO MANEUVER THE TOTE ONTO THE REAR METAL PLATE.  THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE JACK AND TOTE.  IT FEEL OFF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  AS THE TOTE SPLIT, PRODUCT SPLASHED ONTO THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR RECEIVED IMMEDIATE TREATMENT AND WAS RELEASED.  SUNOCO'S HAZMAT TEAM DECONTAMINATED THE EQUIPMENT AND GROUND BY WASHING IT INTO THE PLANTS WATER TREATMENT SYSTEM TO BE NEUTRALIZED.  THIS DISTRICT NO LONGER USES MANUAL PALLET TACKS.  WE ALSO USE A SECURITY DEVICE WHEN MOVING MATERIAL TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO BE UNLOADED.

column168: DOCKMAN ENTERED THE UNIT 5840 AND FOUND IT HAD A SMELL.  AS HE UNLOADED THE TRAILER HE DISCOVERED ONE OF THE DRUMS FROM THIS SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING.  IT WAS ALL OVER THE FLOOR AND VERY STICKY.  AS HE GOT CLOSER HE COULD SEE THE DRUM HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY A FORK LIFT BLADE.

WHEN DOOR WAS OPENED ODOR WAS DETECTED.  SUPV COULD SEE A DRUM ON RIGHT SIDE WITH LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  HE IMMEDIATELY TIPPED THE DRUM ON SIDE TO STOP THE LEAK.  APPROX 5 GALLONS OF THE CONTENTS HAD SPILLED OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.  LEAKING DRUM AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL ARE IN A 95 GALLON OVERPACK SALVAGE DRUM.  DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN ROCKING DURING TRANSIT BANGING UP AGAINST THE KICK PLATE ON TRAILER WALL CAUSING A DENT AND A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CUSTOMER, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A SUBSTANCE ON FLOOR OF TRAILER.  HE THREW DOWN SOME SPEEDY DRY AND INVESTIGATED LOAD.  DRIVER DISCOVERED A TOTE TANK WITH A CRACK NEAR THE TOP OF THE TANK, 3" ABOVE THE LIQUID.  THE CUSTOMER UNLOADED FREIGHT, NEUTRALIZED TRAILER FLOOR AND RELEASED TRAILER AND DRIVER.

RNO RECEIVED TRAILER WITH PALLET ALREADY DAMAGED WHEN DOOR WAS OPENED. TOOK THE PALLETS THAT WERE DAMAGED AND ISOLATED THEM IN A SECURE LOCATION OF THE DOCK.  RNO REPALLETIZED THE FREIGHT OF THE NON DAMAGED ITEMS FOR SHIPPING.  EMAIL MESSAGE WAS SENT TO THE DEN SERVICE CENTER FOR FOLLOW UP.
*PALLET UPSTALKED ON PAIL.  PAIL WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT.  *RECOUPED LIQUID INTO RECOVERY PAIL.  RELABELED AND CALLING SHIPPER FOR RGA# PER DISPOSITION.  REPORT, AUDIT SENT TO ORIGIN FOR FOLLOW UP.

SERVICE CENTERS INVOLVED WITH THE HANDLING OF THE SHIPMENT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.

column168: WHEN UNLOADING TWO PALLETS OF BAGS DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE BAG ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE PALLETS RIPPED AND LEAKING.  APPARENTLY THE PALLET STAGED IN FRONT OF THE PALLET OF BAGS WAS PUSHED INTO IT AND SUBSEQUENTLY RIPPED ONE OF THE BAGS CAUSING THE UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DUNNAGE OF SOME KIND HAD BEEN PLACED IN BETWEEN THE TWO PALLETS.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE BAG ON TOP OF A PALLET OF OTHER BAGS RIPPED AND LEAKING.  HERE THERE WAS OTHER FREIGHT STAGED ON TOP OF THIS PALLET OF BAGS AND THAT TOP FREIGHT RIPPED ONE OF THE BAGS CAUSING AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE.  DAMAGED BAG WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH SPILLED CONTENTS AND SHIPPED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF CARDBOARD OR OTHER DUNNAGE WAS PLACE IN BETWEEN THE TOP AND BOTTOM FREIGHT.

column168: TOTE BEGAN LEAKING FROM VALVE AREA.  HAZ MAT CONTRACTOR CALLED IN TO CONDUCT CLEANUP AND PROPER WASTE DISPOSAL.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER SITE TO MAKE A DELIVERY.  HOSE WAS HOOKED UP AND DELIVERY HAD STARTED WHEN DRIVER NOTICED AN IRREGULARITY IN THE HOSE, SIMILAR TO A BUBBLE.  AS THE DELIVERY CONTINUED, THE DRIVER MONITORED THE IRREGULARITY AND FELT IT WAS ENLARGING, SO HE DECIDED TO STOP THE DELIVERY AND INVESTIGATE FURTHER.  AS THE DRIVER WENT TO TURN OFF THE PUMP, THE HOSE RUPTURED.  DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP, PULLED THE TRAILER'S REMOTE SHUTOFF AS HE EVACUATED THE AREA.  HE THEN TURNED OFF THE TRACTOR ENGINE.  DRIVER CONTACTED CUSTOMER AS WELL AS THE CORPORATE OFFICE.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO 9-1-1 CALL.  NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS WERE REPORTED, NOR WAS THERE ANY OFF-SITE ODOR COMPLAINTS.  LESS THAN 40 POUNDS WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.

WHILE IN TRANSIT BACK TO OUR TERMINAL, DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAK FROM INTERNAL VALVE WITHIN CABINET ON TRAILER.  TRIED TO STOP LEAK BY CLOSING AND OPENING THE INTERNAL VALVE SEVERAL TIMES, BUT LEAK DID NOT STOP.  PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS THE CONTRACTION OF METAL PARTS OF THE VALVE DUE TO EXTREMELY COLD WEATHER.  DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED CORPORATE HEADQUARTERS.  ANOTHER DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED WITH ANOTHER TRAILER TO OFF-LOAD THE LEAKING TRAILER. ONCE ALL LIQUID WAS OFF-LOADED, THE LEAK STOPPED.  TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO PLANT WHERE IT WAS DEGASSED AND SENT OUT FOR REPAIR.  NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS WERE REPORTED, NOR WAS THERE AN ODOR COMPLAINT.  LESS THAN 45 POUNDS WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.  SCHUYLKILL COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AND PA DEP WERE CONTACTED JUST IN CASE THE SITUATION ESCALATED.  THEIR SERVICES WERE NOT REQUIRED.

DRIVER PROPERLY LOADED 5796 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  HE THEN DISCONNECTED VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE AND SCULLY CABLE FROM HIS TRAILER.  HE ALSO DROPPED THE SAFETY BAR ON THE LOADING CONNECTION.  THE DRIVER DID NOT UNHOOK THE TWO LOADING HOSES CONNECTED TO THE TRAILER.  HE THEN GOT IN THE TRUCK AND TRIED TO PULL AWAY STRETCHING BOTH LOADING HOSES AND BENDING SOME PIPING UNTIL A LOADING HEAD BROKE OFF OF THE HOSE AND A LOADING HEAD BROKE OFF OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED, GOT OUT AND ASSESSED THE SITUATION.  HE CALLED THE TERMINAL'S NOTIFICATION NUMBER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AND THEN CALLED HIS MANAGER.  AFTER ALL ARRIVED IT WAS NOTED THAT ALL PRODUCT SPILLED WENT INTO AN OIL/WATER SEPARATOR DRAIN.  PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.

SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO TRANSPORTER BY GENERATOR, AMERICAN METALS RECOVERY CORP, PATERSON, NJ, FOR DISPOSAL TO INMETCO, ELLWOOD CITY, PA.  SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED AS RQ, WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S., 8, UN3264, PGII, WITH THE MAIN COMPONENTS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID (8%), CHROMIC ACID (10%), NITRIC ACID (5%), THE REMAINDER BEING WATER.  SHIPMENT WAS LOADED AT THE GENERATOR'S FACILITY LOCATED AT ONE KASPER STREET ON FEBRUARY 2, 2004.  1.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1725 HRS, DRIVER EXITED I-80 WESTBOUND AT MILE MARKER 246 AT THE REST AREA. 2.  UPON EXITING THE VEHICLE, DRIVER HEARD A "HISSING" NOISE AND OBSERVED REDDISH-COLORED VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE CENTER DOME AREA OF THE TANK TRAILER.  3. LOCAL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE AND BEGAN EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES. EVACUATION OF AREA WITHIN 1000 FEET OF SCENE WAS PERFORMED. 4.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1930 HRS, THE INTERSTATE WAS CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS. EVACUATION AREA WAS EXTENDED TO ONE MILE.  5. TRANSPORTER'S CONTRACTED RESPONSE TEAM, RAPID RESPONSE, ARRIVED ON SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 0100HRS. THERE WERE BRIEFED BY LOCAL RESPONSE PERSONNEL ON SITE.  6. RAPID RESPONSE PERSONNEL EXAMINED TRAILER.  TEMPERATURE OF TRAILER CONTINUING TO DECREASE. 7.  EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AT 0100 HRS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0245 HRS, INTERSTATE WAS REOPENED.  REST AREA REMAINED CLOSED.  8. AT APPROXIMATELY 0700HRS, FEBRUARY 3, 2004, SECOND CARGO TANK ARRIVED ON SCENE FOR TRANSFER OF MATERIAL FROM ORIGINAL CARGO TANK.  9. TRANSFER WAS AFFECTED WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENTS.  10. BOTH CARGO TANK TRAILERS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO GENERATOR.  11. INITIAL CARGO TANK WAS DELIVERED TO GENERATOR AND LIQUID RESIDUE WAS RINSED FROM TANK AND THEN THE CARGO TANK WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTER'S FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HRS, FEBRUARY 3, 2003.  UPON COMPLETION OF ALL INVESTIGATIONS REGARDING THE INCIDENT, A FOLLOW UP REPORT WILL BE TRANSMITTED TO INVOLVED AGENCIES BY TRANSPORTER.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARDBOARD CARTOON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT TWO JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING TWO JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE DOCK.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE TOPS OF THE TWO JUGS BEING DAMAGED BY THE FORKLIFT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A TYCHEM SUIT, GLOVES, AND A NEUTRALIZING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE TWO DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWO UNAFFECTED JUGS WERE SHRINK-WRAPPED TO THE PALLET AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  ONE ROADWAY EXPRESS , INC . EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE FREE PRODUCT.  HE WASHED THE AFFECTED SKIN ON HIS ARM AND REPORTED NO HEALTH EFFECTS.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, THREE DAMAGED THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, ONE- HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A PALLET.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED  THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE,  FIVE GALLON FIBER AND ONE, FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL  BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE THREE DAMAGED DRUMS INTO THREE NEW THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS.  ALL THREE DRUM WILL  BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: THE DRIVER STARTED BY LOADING TH TRUCK AT 2:15 PM IN ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, ILLINOIS.  HE LOADED THE TRUCK BY BLENDING: 5040 GALLONS OF NO. 2 DYED FUEL OIL 2160 GALLONS OF NO. 1 DYED FUEL OIL 7200 GALLONS TOTAL.  HE FINISHED LOADING THE TRUCK AT 2:40 PM AND LEFT ARLINGTON HEIGHTS AT APPROXIMATELY 2:43 PM.  HE DROVE TO AVALON PETROLEUM LOCATED AT 501 N MAIN STREET IN ANTIOCH, ILLINOIS ARRIVING THERE AT APPROXIMATELY 3:53 PM.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO HOOK-UP THE CUSTOMERS PUMP HOSE TO OUR TRUCK MOUNTED PUMP AND THEN HOOK-UP OUR PRODUCT SUPPLY HOSE FROM THE PUMP TO CARGO TANK COMPARTMENT # 4.  HE THEN OPENED ALL VALVES RELATED TO THE PRODUCT DELIVERY INTO ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE THEN OPENED UNLOADING VALVES ON CARGO TANK.  AT APPROXIMATELY 4:10 PM DRIVER ENTERED THE TRUCK START THE MOTOR AND ENGAGE THE PTO TO BEGIN THE PUMP-OFF PROCESS.  AFTER ENGAGING PTO THE DRIVER WAS SETTING THE IDLE UP ON THE TRUCK TO PUMP-OFF SPEED AND NOTICED DYED RED FUEL OIL RUNNING OUT FROM UNDER THE TRUCK.  AT THIS POINT THE CUSTOMER'S PUMP HOSE DISCONNECTED FROM THE PUMP AND ALLOWED FUEL OIL TO DISCHARGE ONTO THE CUSTOMER PARKING LOT.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE THE DRIVER DEVIATED FROM COMPANY PROCEDURES BY FAILING TO SECURE HIS DELIVERY HOSE TO HIS TRACTOR.  ACTIONS TAKEN AT TIME DISCOVERED:  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE TRUCK DOWN AND EXITED THE TRUCK.  HE RAN TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK AND NOTICED THE PUMP HOSE HAD BECOME DISCONNECTED FROM THE PUMP.  HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED DOWN ALL VALVES RELATED TO THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  HE THEN CLOSED DOWN ALL VALVES RELATED TO THE CARGO TANK, AND RAN TO THE OFFICE TO GET HELP.  OFFICE PERSONNEL AND THE DRIVER THEN CLOSED AREA OFF AND PUT DOWN ABSORBENT PADS TO TRY AND CONTAIN THE SPILL ALONG WITH STOPPING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED OUR DISPATCH OFFICE OF THE SPILL.  WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED SET ENVIRONMENTAL, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND CONDUCT, AN EMERGENCY CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  OUR COMPANY ALSO RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY BY SENDING THE SAFETY DIRECTOR NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY.  SET ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SITE FOR THE NEXT TWO DAYS AND WAS AIDED THE FIRST DAY BY ANTIOCH FIRE DEPARTMENT.  SET USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND A PORTABLE VACUUM TO REMOVE THE RED COLORED FUEL OIL WHICH WAS POOLED ON THE SURFACE OF THE PARKING LOT.  SET ALSO USED A BOBCAT FRONT-END LOADER TO SCRAPE IMPACTED SNOW, ICE AND A THIN LAYER OF CRUSHED STONE FROM PARKING LOT WERE REMOVED FROM THE AREA, PLACED INTO TRANSPORT CONTAINERS FOR TRANSPORT TO A LICENSED LANDFILL FOR SAFE DISPOSAL.  SET AND REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ILLINOIS ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY ALSO CONDUCTED A SITE PERIMETER SURVEY AND CONFIRMED THAT NO RED-DYED OIL CAUSED ANY OFF-SITE IMPACTS. SUBSEQUENT SOIL BORINGS AND ANALYTICAL RESULTS FROM THE LABORATORY CONFIRMED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND SAFELY REMOVED FROM THE PARKING LOT.  AC
DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT AND PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM.  SET UP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 19:30 OF FEBRUARY 03, 2004 THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE DETECTED SWELLING OF THE TOP AND BOTTOM OF THE OUTER PACKAGE, CONSISTING OF A 5 GALLON SIZE, PLASTIC PAIL.  ADDITIONALLY AN ODOR, SIMILAR TO ROTTEN EGGS, WAS DETECTED BY THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE.  A GAS CYLINDER EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST (SPECIALIST) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO INSPECT THE PACKAGE.  WHILE THE SPECIALIST WAS IN ROUTE TO THE SITE THE DRIVER RE-INSPECTED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND THE SWELLING OF THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD SUBSIDED AND THE ODOR DETECTED EARLIER BY THE DRIVER WAS NO LONGER PRESENT. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 ON FEBRUARY 04, 2004 THE SPECIALIST ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND OPENED THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THE OUTER PACKAGE CONTAINED ONE CYLINDER OF HYDROGEN SULFIDE, ONE CYLINDER OF CARBON MONOXIDE AND ONE CYLINDER OF ETHYLENE OXIDE.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE OUTER PACKAGE DID NOT CONTAIN ANY PACKING MATERIAL TO SECURE OR CUSHION THE CYLINDERS.  UTILIZING A PORTABLE HYDROGEN SULFIDE DETECTOR, THE SPECIALIST DETECTED HYDROGEN SULFIDE VAPOR WITHIN THE OPENED PAIL AND NEAR THE HYDROGEN SULFIDE CYLINDER VALVE.  THE HYDROGEN SULFIDE CYLINDER AND CYLINDER VALVE WERE DETERMINED TO BE IN EXCELLENT PHYSICAL CONDITION BY THE SPECIALIST.  THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF CORROSION, DENTS, PITTING OR OTHER DEFECTS ASSOCIATED WITH THE CYLINDER OR VALVE.  THE THREADED VALVE OUTLET PLUG (WITH WASHER) WAS IN PLACE.  THE SPECIALIST CHECKED THE HYDROGEN SULFIDE CYLINDER VALVE AND FOUND THAT IT WAS NOT SECURELY TIGHTENED.  THE CYLINDER VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY TIGHTENED BY THE SPECIALIST.  THE SPECIALIST ALSO CHECKED THE VALVE OUTLET PLUG WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSELY THREADED INTO THE VALVE OUTLET.  THE SPECIALIST SECURELY TIGHTENED THE OUTLET PLUG.  THE CYLINDER WAS SECURED WITHIN AN OVERPACK, THE OVERPACK PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND ALL ON-SITE ACTIVITIES COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 ON FEBRUARY 04, 2004.  THE CYLINDER WAS DELIVERED TO SET ENVIRONMENTAL, THE DESIGNATED CONSIGNEE ON FEBRUARY 9, 2004.  THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE RESULT OF THE CYLINDER VALVE OPENING SLIGHTLY DURING SHIPMENT WHICH IN TURN CAUSED THE SWELLING OF THE OUTER PACKAGE.  SINCE THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS LACKING A PACKING MATERIAL TO CUSHION THE CYLINDERS, IT IS SUSPECTED THAT THE CYLINDERS WERE ABLE TO MOVE FREELY WITHIN THE OUTER PACKAGES WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE VALVE OPENING DURING SHIPMENT.  ADDITIONALLY, ALTHOUGH A VALVE OUTLET PLUG WAS THREADED INTO THE VALVE OUTLET, IT WAS NOT SECURELY TIGHTENED.  PROPERLY SECURING THE OUTLET PLUG BY THE SHIPPER MAY HAVE PREVENTED THE VAPOR RELEASE.  RECOMMENDATIONS TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS INCLUDE: 1. ENSURE THAT CYLINDER VALVES ARE SECURELY TIGHTENED PRIOR TO SHIPPING.  2. ENSURE THAT CYLINDER OUTLET PLUGS (WITH WASHER) ARE IN PLACE AND SECURELY TIGHTENED PRIOR TO SHIPPING AND, 3. ENSURE THAT CYLINDERS ARE SECURELY CUSHIONED, IN ACCORDANCE WITH 173.24A (3), TO CONTROL MOVEMENT OF THE CYLINDERS WITHIN THE OUTER PACKAGE.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 18, 2004, ONE OF OUR DRIVERS BROUGHT A LOADED TRUCK TO THE LOCATION TO AWAIT DELIVERY BY A RELIEF DRIVER.  APPARENTLY, A HAIRLINE CRACK HAD OCCURRED IN THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER, AND GONE UNDETECTED BY THE DRIVER.  THE TRAILER HAD BEEN RECENTLY CERTIFIED (OCTOBER, 2003) AND ALL REQUIRED TESTS ARE CURRENT.  APPROXIMATELY FIVER HOURS PASSED UNTIL THE RELIEF DRIVER ARRIVED TO TAKE THE TRUCK.  DURING THIS INTERVAL DIESEL WAS RIPPING FROM THE REAR COMPARTMENT ON TO THE GROUND.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RELIEF DRIVE NOTICED THE RELEASE AND REPORTED THE LEAK TO HIS SUPERVISORS.  RECOVERY EFFORTS BEGAN IMMEDIATELY.  THE GROUND WAS FROZEN AND ROCKY, CIRCUMSTANCES THAT AIDED RECOVERY.  A BACKHOE WORKING NEARLY WAS HIRED TO EXCAVATE A TRENCH NEAR THE EFFECTED AREA (APPROXIMATELY 36"  WIDE X 24" DEEP BY 20' FEET LONG).  THE TRENCH WAS LINED WITH PLASTIC AND INCORPORATED A SUMP.  FROM THIS SUMP, APPROXIMATELY 225 GALLONS OF DIESEL HAS BEEN RECOVERED TO DATE.  BY METERING THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE COMPARTMENT IT IS CALCULATED THAT 400 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE WYOMING DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY ON THE MORNING OF FEBRUARY 19, 2004.  ADDITIONALLY, WE HAVE HAD SEVERAL CONVERSATIONS WITH THE LANDOWNER WHO IS COMFORTABLE WITH OUR EFFORTS TO DATE.  THE TRAILER IS BEING REPAIRED AND RETESTED. RECOVERY EFFORTS CONTINUE AND WE ARE CONSIDERING THE POSSIBILITY OF "LAND FARMING" THE EFFECTED SOIL.

column168: THE TRACTOR TRAILER DRIVER IN THIS INCIDENT HAD STOPPED FOR A TIRE CHECK WHEN HE NOTICED FLASHES OF LIGHT COMING FROM THE TOP FRONT OF THE CONTAINER.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED OUR DISPATCHER AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  HE WAS ADVISED TO MOVE THE UNIT TO A SAFER LOCATION AWAY FROM THE PUBLIC AND PRIVATE PROPERTY, THEN NOTIFY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT FOR ASSISTANCE. JBK SAFETY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE MANUFACTURER, THE SHIPPER, THE CONSIGNEE, AND THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER. THE SPILL CENTER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY CONTACTED THE APPROPRIATE STATE AND LOCAL AGENCIES. THE MANUFACTURER DISPATCHED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND THEY ARRIVES APPROX. 9 HRS. AFTER RECEIVING THEIR NOTIFICATION.  THE LEAKING TRAILER MODULE WAS MOVE APPROX. 1 MILE NORTH OF BEACH, ND ON COUNTY ROAD #16.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM OFF LOADED THE LEAKING CYLINDER'S PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER EMPTY TRAILER WHICH THEY HAD TRANSPORTED TO THE SCENE.  THE LEAKING CYLINDER WAS THEN INSERTED WITH GASEOUS NITROGEN, CHECKED AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO MORRISVILLE, PA.  THIS INCIDENT IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY WATER FREEZING NEXT TO AN INTERNAL SAFETY BURST DISC ALLOWING SILANE GAS TO REACH THE ATMOSPHERE AND THE AUTO-IGNITE.  EXACT CAUSE IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.  ALL TERMINALS THAT TRANSPORT THIS PRODUCT WERE NOTIFIED AND TOLD TO HAVE THIS INCIDENT DISCUSSED AT THEIR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE THE TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY DRIVER WAS TURNING TO ENTER BASF CORPORATION PROPERTY IN BELVIDERE, NEW JERSEY, APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK-TRAILER.  WHILE ON BASF CORPORATION PROPERTY, AN ADDITIONAL ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASES WERE THE RESULT OF IMPROPERLY RE-AFFIXED VALVE-BOLTS ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  NO SOIL, DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED.  THE NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, THE NEW JERSEY STATE POLICE, THE BELVIDERE POLICE DEPARTMENT, AND THE BELVIDERE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE FACILITY.  BASF CORPORATION PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP AND COORDINATED DISPOSAL FOR ALL WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP.  THE REAR VALVE-BOLTS ON THE TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY TANK-TRAILER WERE REPAIRED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DRIVER HAD PULLED OFF THE INTERSTATE AT EXIT 30 TO TAKE A BREAK.  BEFORE DOING SO, HE MADE A WALK AROUND OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER AND THAT TIME NOTICED AN ODOR OF THE PRODUCT HE WAS TRANSPORTING.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION HE DISCOVERED WHAT APPEARED TO BE PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE FRAME AROUND THE DOLLY LEGS.  IT WAS RAINING HOWEVER WHICH MADE IT DIFFICULT TO ACTUALLY TELL IF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING OR WHERE IT MAY BE LEAKING FROM.  HE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE CARGO TANK TO CONTAIN WHAT HE THOUGHT MAY BE WATER MIXED WITH PRODUCT AND CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE.  AS TIME PAST THE ODOR OF THE PRODUCT WAS NO LONGER PRESENT.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SOURCE OF THE PROBLEM WAS A DEFECTIVE AS WELL AS LOOSE CLEAN OUT CAP ON TOP OF THE TRAILER THAT MAY HAVE ALLOWED JUST ENOUGH PRODUCT TO ESCAPE TO MAKE A NOTICEABLE ODOR.  A NEW GASKET WAS PLACED ON THE CLEANOUT CAP.  AND NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE NOTED.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED ON TO MAKE HIS DELIVERY WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

column168: DRIVER PROCEEDING NORTHEAST ON U.S. 171 (ARCHER AVE) ATTEMPTING RIGHT TURN ONTO 1ST AVENUE (EASTBOUND).  DRIVER WAS GOING TO FAST FOR RIGHT TURN CONDITIONS AND ULTIMATELY ROLLED THE VEHICLE ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE OF THE UNIT.  ONCE IT HIT THE GROUND, THE UNIT SLID INTO THE MEDIUM CURB CAUSING RUPTURE TO THE TRANSPORT ON THE UPPER REAR OF COMPARTMENT #4 AND TO THE UPPER REAR OF COMPARTMENT #1.  APPROXIMATE LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS 2000 GALLONS BEFORE TRANSPORT COULD BE PUMPED OFF AND REMAINING PRODUCT RETAINED IN ANOTHER TRANSPORT.  ALL APPROPRIATE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS INITIATING ALL ENVIRONMENTAL EFFORTS BY RESPONSE TEAMS.  ALL DRIVERS ARE CURRENTLY IN TRAINING FOR RE-EVALUATION ON PREVENTIVE ROLLOVERS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 59 NORTHBOUND IN GADSDEN, ALABAMA, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK HAD BEEN DENTED ON THE LEFT SIDE, WHICH CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE.  THE SADDLE TANK ON THE VEHICLE WAS ALSO DAMAGED, WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  THE ALABAMA STATE POLICE, ALABAMA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, REECE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, ATTALLA FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND ETOWAH COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  OIL DRY WAS APPLIED TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES PUMPED THE REMAINING FREE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER INTO ANOTHER TANK TRUCK PROVIDED BY SERVICE TRANSPORT COMPANY. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES ALSO EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, AND REMOVED THE SPENT OIL DRY FROM THE IMPACTED AREA.  APPROXIMATELY 7 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND OIL DRY WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP.  DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.  ONE LANE OF INTERSTATE 59 NORTHBOUND WAS CLOSED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT FOR APPROXIMATELY 12 HOURS.  NO ADDITIONAL PLANS EXIST AT THIS TIME.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 22, 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS, A RAILWAY TANK CAR LTCX 1814, LOADED WITH ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID/NON-FLAMMABLE GAS/2.2/UN1951 WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) KANSAS CITY YARD.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO THE SITE AND REPORTED A PARTIALLY OPEN BLEED VALVE AND A PARTIALLY OPEN UNLOAD LINE VALVE.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONDER SECURED BOTH VALVES, THUS CORRECTING THE RELEASE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.

IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK THROUGH A CARGO PUMP MOUNTED ON CARRIER'S VEHICLE TO CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING LINE WHEN CARRIER'S CARGO HOSE FAILED.  THE FAILED HOSE WAS CONNECTED FROM CARRIER'S CARGO PUMP TO CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING LINE.  SEPARATION OCCURRED WHERE HOSE END IS PERMANENTLY FASTENED TO STAINLESS STEEL CAMLOCK FITTING.  WHEN PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK, CARRIER'S DRIVER DISENGAGED THE CARGO PUMP AND CLOSED VALVES.  20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. CONSIGNEE RECOVERED SPILLED MATERIAL.  FAILED CARGO HOSE WAS REPLACED AND DELIVERY COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  FAILURE IS UNDER INVESTIGATION.  FAILED HOSE WAS SENT TO MANUFACTURER TO DETERMINE CAUSE. MATERIALS OF CONSTRUCTION WERE RECOMMENDED BY MANUFACTURER FOR THE PRODUCTED BEING DELIVERED.  ONCE INVESTIGATION IS COMPLETED, CORRECTIVE ACTIONS SHALL BE IDENTIFIED AND IMPLEMENTED.

GPLU 420015 WAS NOTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BY CARRIER PERSONNEL.  THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. FRA INSPECTOR RAMSEY RESPONDED AND FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LOOSE, ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE, THE AIR VALVE CAP LOOSE AND THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF DEVICE INOPERABLE.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED AL LOOSE CAPS AND BOLTS STOPPING THE RELEASE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment; Rollover Accident
column168: SUBJECT TANK CARS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT OF CSXT TRAIN Q40605. THE RPBX 17142 WAS OVERTURNED IN THE DERAILMENT ON ITS SIDE AND WAS STRUCK IN THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE TANK CAR BY ANOTHER TANK CAR (RPBX 176308). THE IMPACT OF THE COLLISION CAUSED A BREACH IN THE TANK JACKET AND TANK SHELL.  THE BREECH IN THE TANK SHELL WAS A CRACK APPROXIMATELY 6 INCHES IN LENGTH AND 3/8 OF AN INCH IN WIDTH.  THE TWO TANK CARS CAME TO REST IN A "T" SHAPE, WITH THE END OF THE RPBX 176308 INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE RPBX 17142.  ONCE THE CARS WERE SEPARATED, THE CRACK IN THE TANK SHELL WAS DISCOVERED.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF RPBX 17142 WAS THEN PUMPED OFF INTO VACUUM TRUCKS.  ESTIMATE THAT 8,800 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THE RPBX 17142.  THE WACX 151179 WAS OVERTURNED ON IT'S SIDE IN THE DERAILMENT AND CAME TO REST WITH IT'S TOP ROLLED OVER 500 FROM VERTICAL.  THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WAS STRUCK BY A BOX CAR.  THE MANWAY LID WAS HIT AND DAMAGED IN THE COLLISION.  THREE OF THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE KNOCKED LOOSE OR BENT, THE MANWAY NOZZLE WAS ALSO DENTED.  THIS RESULTED IN THE SLOW RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  ATTEMPTS TO SECURE THE MANWAY LID WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED WHEN THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED WITH A CRANE.  ESTIMATE 150 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE LOST FROM THIS CAR.  THE RPBX 17108 WAS OVERTURNED AND CAME TO REST ON IT'S SIDE WITH THE TOP FITTINGS APPROXIMATELY 1200 FROM VERTICAL.  PRODUCT WAS FOUND TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE MOUNTING FLANGE, BETWEEN THE GASKET MATERIAL AND THE MOUNTING FLANGE PLATE.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY ROLLING THE TANK CAR BACK TO A VERTICAL ORIENTATION USING A CRANE.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THIS CAR.  CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILLED ACID FROM ALL THREE CARS WERE ACCOMPLISHED BY EXCAVATING A CATCH PIT INTO WHICH THE SPILLED ACID FLOWED.  ALL FREE LIQUIDS WERE SUBSEQUENTLY PUMPED OFF FROM THIS PIT AND ALL IMPACTED SOILS EXCAVATED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

ON FEBRUARY 20, 2004, CSX PERSONNEL IN THE HAWESVILLE, KY RAILYARD OBSERVED THREE LOADED SODIUM HYDROXIDE TANK CARS (HOKX 111160, HOKX 111365 AND HOKX 8060) WITH PRODUCT ON THEIR SIDES.  THE CAR WERE ISOLATED, THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL FOUND SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE ON THE TOPS AND SIDES OF THE THREE CARS, IN A PATTERN THAT INDICATED THE PRODUCT RELIEVED FROM THE RECLOSING-STYLE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE. column168: ON FEBRUARY 19, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 1:20 PM, I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM N&M DRIVER TOM HEINEMANN INDICATING HE FOUND SPILLED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN HIS TRAILER.  TOM WAS PARKED IN THE DOCK AT THE 3M COMPANY, PRAIRE DU CHIEN, WI WHEN HE FIRST DISCOVERED THE SPILL.  THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 11 BULK BAGS (1107 LBS EACH) OF A SOLID POISON MATERIAL, DIAMINODIPHENYLMETHANE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO 3M COMPANY WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY MR. HEINEMAN.  THE 11 PALLETS IN THIS SHIPMENT EACH HELD ONE BULK BAG.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOADED IN TO THIS TRAILER IN THE EARLY A.M. HOURS BY A DOCK EMPLOYEE AT N&M TRANSFER CO.  NO SPILL INCIDENT OF ANY KIND WAS REPORTED BY THE DOCK EMPLOYEE LOADING THE TRAILER, NOR WAS THERE ANY SPILL REPORT ISSUED BY THE FOREMAN OR SUPERVISOR WHO SUPERVISED THE LOADING.  PLEASE SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS.  THE RUPTURED PALLET IS LOADED ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  IT'S MY UNDERSTANDING THAT THE RUPTURED BAG IS EITHER THE FIRST OR SECOND PALLET LOADED (TOWARDS THE NOSE) ON THE LEFT SIDE.  THE AMOUNT OF RUPTURED MATERIAL TRAVELED BACKWARDS TOWARD THE TRAILER DOOR, COVERING THE FLOOR AREA UNDERNEATH THE PALLETS LOADED BEHIND THE RUPTURED SKID.  THE SPILLED MATERIALS WERE IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP BY THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE 3M COMPANY.  INITIAL CLEAN UP WAS USE OF A WET VAC.  A WATER TREATMENT OF SOME FORM WAS THEN USED TO REMOVE THE REMAINING RESIDUE OFF OF THE TRAILER FLOOR.  AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT THIS CAUSE OF THE RUPTURE OF THIS MATERIAL IS UNKNOWN.  MR. ROBERT JONES (OWNERS OF BALL WAREHOUSE, THE SHIPPER) ADVISED ME BY PHONE CALL ON FRIDAY 2/20 THAT AT HIS FACILITY THESE BULK BAGS ARE REMOVED FROM THE "CHINESE" PALLETS THAT THEY ARRIVED ON AND ARE THEN PLACED ON A STURDIER 4 X 4 PALLET.  A SLIP SHEET IS FIRST PLACED UNDER THE BAG ON TOP OF PALLET.  AFTER THE BAGS ARE PLACED SQUARELY ON A PALLET THEY ARE SHRINK WRAPPED TO THE PALLET.  ELLEN SCHIEBER, SAFETY ENGINEER AT 3M COMPANY, ALSO ADVISED ME ON FRIDAY 2/20 THAT THERE WAS A PUNCTURE IN THE BAG APPROXIMATELY 6" WIDE.  THE AREA OF THE PUNCTURE WAS DIRECTLY UNDER THE BAG.  IT WAS NOT NEAR ANY OF THE BOTTOM EXTERIOR AREA OF THE BAG.  THE SIZE OF THIS PUNCTURE WOULD BE SIMILAR TO THE WIDTH OF A FORK ON A TOWMOTOR.  STRANGELY ENOUGH, ELLEN ALSO NOTED THAT NEITHER THE SLIP SHEET BELOW THE BAG, OR ANY OF THE BOARDS FROM THE PALLET, WERE DAMAGED IN ANY WAY.  OUR ONLY CONCLUSION WAS THEN THE BAG WAS PUNCTURED ONLY AFTER IT HAD BEEN MOVED FROM IT'S ORIGINAL "CHINESE" PALLET.  THE 20 LBS OF SPILLED POISON SOLID REMAINED CONFINED TO AN AREA TOTALLY WITHIN THE TRAILER.  THAT AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR IS APPROXIMATELY 10 FEET BY 6 FEET.  THE APPROXIMATE 20 LBS OF SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ADDED (FOR PROPER DISPOSAL) TO THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STREAM AT 3M COMPANY.  DURING THE 2-3 HOURS OF CLEAN UP OF THIS MATERIAL, NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE OF ANY KIND WAS REPORTED. MY ONLY RECOMMENDATION FOR FUTURE HANDLING OF THIS MATERIAL WOULD BE INCREASED CAUTI

THE PAIL WAS DROPPED DURING HANDLING CAUSING LEAKAGE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED.  UNDAMAGED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column42: HYDRAZINE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, WITH NOT MORE THAN 37 PERCENT HYDRAZINE, BY MASS
column168: AT APPROX. 12:15 PM. OUR DRIVER, LARRY DICKSON (LARRY), ARRIVED AT THE FRONT GATE OF THE DIABLO CANYON NUCLEAR POWER PLANT TO DELIVER (2) TWO TOTES OF HYDRAZINE 35% SOLUTION, PRODUCT NUMBER 729862, FOR OUR CUSTOMER, PACIFIC GAS & ELECTRIC (PG&E).  AFTER VERIFYING LARRY'S IDENTIFICATION, HE MOVED OUR TRUCK INSIDE THE GATE AND ALONGSIDE THE GUARD SHACK FOR INSPECTION.  THIS IS A NEW PROCEDURE SINCE THE EVENTS OF 9-11, THE GATE AND GUARD SHACK ARE APPROXIMATELY 7 MILES FROM THE PLANT DOWN AN ACCESS ROAD. THERE IS A FULL TIME CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL OFFICER STATIONED AT THE GATE.  ONCE OUR TRUCK WAS INSIDE THE GATE, THE GUARDS OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRAILER, TO VERIFY THE CARGO, AND NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID (APPROX.. 2 PINTS) ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND ON THE TOP OF ONE OF THE TWO TOTES OF HYDRAZINE.  IT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN COMING FROM THE TOP CLOSURE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  PG&E'S SECURITY NOTIFIED THE CHP OFFICER WHO IN TURN, CALLED THE SAN LUIS OBISPO FIRE DEPT.  LARRY THEN CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR, ARTHUR DUIM, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED ME OF THE INCIDENT AT APPROX. 12:40 P.M.  AFTER SPEAKING WITH LARRY MYSELF I CONTACTED OUR REGULATORY MANAGER, MICHAEL NASSRALLA, AND DISTRICT MANAGER, GEORGE MARTIN. I THEN CONTACTED PG&E TO SEE IF THEY COULD DEAL WITH THE SITUATION.  I SPOKE WITH STEVE REED AT PG & E AND HE TOLD ME THEY HAD AN ON-SITE FIRE DEPT. THAT HAS HANDLED THESE SITUATIONS BEFORE AND THAT HE WOULD HAVE THEM CHECK THE SITUATION OUT.  PG&E FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE FRONT GATE AND TOLD THE SECURITY OFFICERS TO MAKE LARRY BACK OUT OF THE GATE, OFF OF THEIR PROPERTY AND PARK THE VEHICLE ON A STRIP OF BEACH ALONGSIDE AVILA BEACH DRIVE, APPROX. 20' FROM A GROUP OF TRAVEL TRAILERS WHO WERE CAMPING THERE.  SAN LUIS OBISPO FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED ON SCENE AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION FROM THE POINT.  I SPOKE WITH KERRY BOYLE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR FOR THE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND TOLD HIM THAT PG&E WAS GOING TO HANDLE THE SITUATION..  MR. BOYLE STATED THAT STEVE REED DID NOT HAVE THE AUTHORITY TO MAKE THAT DECISION, AND NOW THAT THE VEHICLE WAS ON THE PUBLIC BEACH, PG&E HAD NO JURISDICTION.  MR. BOYLE ASKED ME SOME QUESTIONS ON HOW TO RESPOND TO THE LEAK.  HIS CONCERN WAS TO STOP THE IMMEDIATE LEAK. I EXPLAINED TO HIM THAT THE CONTAINER WAS NOT PRESSURIZED AND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE FROM THE LID, SO THERE WILL NOT BE AND FURTHER LEAKAGE UNLESS THE VEHICLE IS MOVED.  I THEN TOLD HIM THAT WE HAD OUTSIDE CONTRACTORS WHO COULD BE SENT TO THE SCENE AND TAKE CARE OF THE SITUATION, HOWEVER, DO TO THE LOCATION, IT WOULD TAKE SEVERAL HOURS TO RESPOND.  MR. BOYLE TOLD ME TO DISPATCH SOMEONE RIGHT AWAY AND INSISTED THEY WEAR LEVEL A PPE.  I CONTACTED MP ENVIRONMENTAL (MP) IN BAKERSFIELD WHO TOLD ME THEY DID NOT HAVE RESOURCES TO HANDLE THE SITUATION.  MP RECOMMENDED I CALL ACTI OUT OF BAKERSFIELD, CA.  I SPOKE WITH RON MICHAELS AT ACTI WHO PUT A TEAM TOGETHER FOR ME AND DISPATCHED THEM TO THE SCENE AT 2:40 P.M

column42: HYDRAZINE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, WITH NOT MORE THAN 37 PERCENT HYDRAZINE, BY MASS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:20 A.M., I RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM OUR DRIVER, LARRY DICKSON (LARRY), WHO INFORMED ME THAT THE TOTE OF HYDRAZINE FROM THE PREVIOUS NIGHT'S INCIDENT AT PACIFIC GAS & ELECTRIC, WAS ONCE AGAIN LEAKING.  SAN LUIS OBISPO'S HAZ-MAT TEAM HANDLED THE INCIDENT BY TIGHTENING DOWN THE BOLT RING ON THE TOP OF THE TOTE, PRIOR TO US TRANSPORTING IT BACK TO OXNARD.  I CONTACTED OUR REGULATORY MANAGER, MICHAEL NASSRALLA, AND, DISTRICT MANAGER, GEORGE MARTIN.  MICHAEL LEFT A MESSAGE FOR DWIGHT LANDRY FOR GUIDANCE ON THE SECOND REPORTING OF THE SAME INCIDENT.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT THIS WAS A SEPARATE INCIDENT AND MICHAEL MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS/REPORTS.  I CONTACTED ECOLOGY CONTROL INC. (ECI) AND SPOKE WITH TERRY SULLIVAN.  I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO HER AND SHE SENT A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE LA/GARFIELD FACILITY TO PICK UP A NEW GASKET FOR THE TOTE AND THEN PROCEED TO THE OXNARD FACILITY TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  AFTER DISCUSSING THE INCIDENT FURTHER WITH GEORGE MARTIN, IT WAS DECIDED THAT I WOULD GO TO THE OXNARD FACILITY TO HANDLE THE SITUATION.  I HAD ED GAMBLIN, INSIDE SALES REPRESENTATIVE FOR THE OXNARD BRANCH, CONTACT THE CITY OF OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EXPLAIN TO THEM WHAT HAPPENED AND WHAT WE WERE DOING ABOUT IT.  I TOLD ED TO GIVE THE CITY OF OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT MY CELL PHONE NUMBER AND I WOULD EXPLAIN OUR PROPOSED RESPONSE.  I WAS CONTACTED BY GREG ABILLE, ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST FOR THE CITY OF OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT/CUPA DIVISION.  GREG AND I SPOKE WHILE I WAS EN-ROUTE TO OXNARD.  I EXPLAINED IN DETAIL WHAT MY PROPOSED RESPONSE WAS GOING TO BE AND WE ALSO SPOKE OF THE PREVIOUS NIGHT'S INCIDENT.  GREG HAD SEEN IT ON THE NEWS AND KNEW THAT THIS WAS A RELATED INCIDENT.  GREG AGREED TO LET ME AND ECI HANDLE THIS WITH THE CITY OF OXNARD FIRE DEPARTMENT AS BACK-UP OPTION.  HE GAVE ME A CELL PHONE NUMBER TO CALL IF ANYTHING HAPPENED AND INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL HIM WHEN THE PROJECT WAS COMPLETED.  I ARRIVED ON SITE AT 5:30 P.M. ECI HAD NOT ARRIVED YET.  I PLACED A COUPLE OF CALLS TO FIND OUT THEIR EXPECTED TIME OF ARRIVAL.  I HAD ONE OF THE OXNARD TRUCK DRIVERS ON STAND BY SO THAT WE COULD MOVE THE TRAILER FOR DECONTAMINATION. ECI ARRIVED AT 6:45 P.M. WITH A THREE-MAN RESPONSE TEAM.  I EXPLAINED WHAT NEEDED TO BE DONE AND AFTER A REVIEW OF THE MSDS, AND A SHORT TAIL-GATE SAFETY MEETING, ECI PROCEEDED TO DON THEIR LEVEL "B" PPE.  UPON ENTRY THE TEAM FOUND THAT APPROX. 4 PINTS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP CLOSURE OF THE TOTE.  SAN LUIS OBISPO'S HAZ-MAT TEAM HAD INDEED TIGHTENED THE BOLT RING DOWN ON THE TOTE; HOWEVER, THEY FAILED TO ENSURE THE LID WAS ON STRAIGHT BEFORE DOING SO.  AS A RESULT, MORE HYDRAZINE AGAIN LEAKED OUT ONTO THE TOP OF THE TOTE, WITH A SMALL AMOUNT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. ECI OPENED THE LID, PUT ON THE NEW GASKET AS A PRECAUTION AND PROPERLY CLOSED THE CONTAINER.  USING ABSORBENT RAGS, ECI CLEANED UP THE MATERIAL AND PLACED THE RAGS IN PLASTIC BAG FOR DISPOSAL.  ONCE THE SITUATION WAS STABILIZ

RICHARD NOTICED WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TRAILER THAT THERE WERE 3 MORE CARTONS BETWEEN SKIDS AND PROCEEDED TO REMOVE FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON REMOVING HE NOTICED 2 OF THE CARTONS HAD WET STAINS ON THEM.  THE THIRD CARTON WAS SOAKED AND HAD SMOKE COMING OUT OF IT. RICHARD THEN LEFT THE TRAILER AND CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR.  THE SUPERVISOR ISOLATED THE AREA AND HAD THE TRAILER PULLED TO THE YARD. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY.  THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS IMPROPER LOADING OF SHIPMENT NUMBER CHI 6100011.  ONYZ SPECIAL SERVICE WAS CONTRACTED FOR CLEAN- UP OF THE SPILL. SNOW ADVISED THE ACFX 89983 WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION ONCE REPAIRS WERE MADE.

TIM WELLMAN, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS PHOENIX, AZ., REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR, IDENTIFIED AS MWSX 29631, LOCATED IN YARD ONE, TRACK 131.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, OR WATER CONTAMINATION.  DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED WITH ERI, A UP CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND.  AT 4:51 PM, MANAGER JOHNSON REPORTED THAT THE CONTRACTOR HAD FOUND A LEAK FROM THE LIQUID LINE ASSEMBLY ON TOP OF THE CAR.  MR. JOHNSON ADVISED THE ASSEMBLY WAS LOOSE AND IT WAS TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE ASSEMBLY APPEARED TO BE NEW AND WASN'T PROPERLY SECURED.  AFTER REPAIRS WERE MADE AND THE LEAK STOPPED, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED CONTAINER OCLU 094917 HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING BY A DRAYMAN ATTEMPTING TO PULL A LOAD AT THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CA.  INSPECTION NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, ONE DROP EVERY FIVE SECONDS, WHICH APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON POOLED ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND CONTAINED PENDING INSPECTION.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED.  LOADING AND BLOCKING AND BRACING APPEARED TO BE IN ACCORDANCE WITH AAR PAMPHLET 6C.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO OFF LOAD AND INSPECT THE DRUMS TO FIND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  LOCATED FIVE DRUMS FROM THE FLOOR TIER AT THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER THAT HAD DAMAGE TO THE BOTTOM CHIMES FROM CONTACT WITH THE METAL FLOORING PLATE.  THE PLATE WAS BENT IN SEVERAL LOCATIONS, PROVIDING AN UNEVEN PLATFORM FOR THE DRUMS TO SIT ON.  ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME WHERE THE METAL PLATE RUBBED THROUGH THE CHIME.  ESTIMATED EIGHT TO TEN GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS, AND ARRANGEMENTS ARE BEING MADE TO RETURN THE DRUMS TO THE MANUFACTURER, PER THEIR REQUEST.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND THE CONTAINER RELEASED TO P&O NEDLLOYD FOR REPAIR.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO CONTAINER CRXU 220646 AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: CRAIG CHERNE, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, DELORES YARD, REPORTED RANDY, KINDER MORGAN, HAD ADVISED THAT TANKCAR ACFX 95980, WAS ON UNLOADING TRACK 41946 OF THE KINDER MORGAN FACILITY AND DRIPPING FROM A CRACK AT THE BOLSTER FRAME MOUNT ABOVE THE AXLE.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED WITH MR. CHERNE WHO REPORTED THE UNION PACIFIC WAS SCHEDULED TO PICK UP THE TANKCAR.  MR. COOPER ADVISED THAT KINDER MORGAN WOULD HAVE TO EMPTY THE TANKCAR AND CLEAN IT PRIOR TO THE UNION PACIFIC SWITCHING THE CAR.  ON FEB 15TH, THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE MOVED FROM CARSON, TO COLTON, CA., WHERE IT WAS CAPTURED, PLACED ON BAD ORDER HOLD, AND SET TO THE ONE SPOT CAR REPAIR TRACK, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND INSPECTED.  KINDER MORGAN PERSONNEL COULD NOT IDENTIFY WHICH END OF THE CAR THE LEAKED WAS OBSERVED, BUT STATED ONLY A FEW GALLONS DRIPPED FROM THE CAR PRIOR TO BEING NOTICED. A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE CAR FAILED TO LOCATE ANY VISIBLE STRESS CRACKS AT EITHER BOLSTER.  INTERIOR INSPECTION FOUND THE CAR TO BE ALMOST EMPTY, WITH A FEW GALLONS OF RESIDUE PRODUCT REMAINING.  THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER, AG PROCESSING, WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND REQUESTED TO APPLY FOR AN FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY PRIOR TO THE CAR MOVING ANY FURTHER. MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FRA 04020057, WAS OBTAINED ON 3-3-04
